You can use the std::next_permutation function to compute the lexicographically next bit permutation in C++. Here is some sample code:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  string bits = "0011"; // input bit string

  // sort the bit string in lexicographical order
  sort(bits.begin(), bits.end()); 

  // generate all possible permutations of the sorted bit string
  do {
    cout << bits << endl;
  } while (next_permutation(bits.begin(), bits.end()));

  return 0;
}
```

This code first sorts the input bit string in lexicographical order, then generates all possible permutations of the sorted bit string using the `std::next_permutation` function. Each permutation is printed to the console. The first permutation printed will be the input bit string, and subsequent permutations will be in lexicographically increasing order.
